title: baumkuchen
body: German for "log cake" or "tree cake". A layered [[cake]] baked on a spit, which gives it its hollow circle design. When sliced, the layers make the cake resemble tree rings. It is popular in Japan including because it is a popular return present for wedding guests because of its ring shape, similar to the symbol of the Zen Enso symbolizing good luck. Karl Joseph Wilhelm Juchheim introduced it to Japan at a 1919 German exhibition in Hiroshima, and two years later, he and his wife founded the Jochheim Company, which continues to sell baumkuchen and other sweets according to Juchheim's original recipe in pastry shops throughout the country. h4. Related * Tag Group: [[Tag Group:Food Tags|Food]] * "Wikipedia":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baumkuchen]

body:
An action role-playing game developed by Square Enix for the PlayStation 4. The game is a full remake of the original [[Final Fantasy VII]] first released in 1997.

title: sample_watermark
body:
An image containing the word "Sample" (often in all caps) as a [[watermark]] anywhere on the image, typically covering the entire image. In Japanese, the word for sample is サンプル, さんぷる, 見本, or みほん.

Such measures were typically used on a "sample" image of a certain products (posters, cards, dakimakura, etc.) to prevent counterfeiting.

A character from [[Fate/stay night]]. He is a [[priest]] that oversees the 5th Holy Grail War.

In [[Fate/stay night]], Kotomine is in his mid 30's with slightly long [[brown hair]] and blank [[brown eyes]]. He wears a black bishop class priest uniform with, usually opened, dark purple [[cassock]] with golden [[cross]]. title: wave_motion_gun
body:
[b]The Wave Motion Gun[/b] (波動砲, [i]Hadou Hou[/i]) is a weapon which appeared in the [[Uchuu Senkan Yamato]] [[science fiction|science fiction]] anime series from the 70s.

This special weapon is the "trump card" of the [[Yamato (Uchuu Senkan Yamato)|Space Battleship Yamato]]. 

The Wave Motion Gun functions by connecting the Wave Motion Engine to the enormous firing gate at the ship's bow, enabling the tachyon energy power of the engine to be fired in a stream directly forwards. 

Enormously powerful, it can vapourise an entire fleet of enemy ships with one shot; however, it takes a brief but critical period to charge before firing.

A little known fact is that the creator of [[Street Fighter]] created [[Ryu (street fighter)|]]'s "[[Hadouken]]" attack inspired by the Hadou Hou.

The main cannon of the [[SDF-1]] from [[Macross]] was also inspired by this weapon.

h4.See also

* [[andromeda_(uchuu_senkan_yamato)|Space Battleship Andromeda]]
* [[hadouhou]] (disambiguation page)

title: hot_wheels
body:
A popular line of diecast toy [[car]]s and other vehicles by Mattel, featuring both fantasy vehicles and licensed real world vehicles. Hot Wheels are not made to scale, though they are roughly equivalent to the size of a 1/64 model. The line has inspired various video games, animated movies, and TV cartoon series.

Hot Wheels has collaborated with numerous popular copyrights including [[Fast & Furious]], [[Need for Speed]], [[Forza]], [[Gran Turismo]], [[Halo (series)|]], [[Star Wars]], [[Barbie (franchise)|]], [[Marvel]], [[DC Comics]] and [[Disney]], as well as some real world motorsports series. The collaborations vary in form, including recreations of fictional or custom cars, existing models featuring themed graphics, and original fantasy cars designed as [[vehicalization]]s of characters from those copyrights.

h4. Tagged Original Models

title: yf-29
body:
A [[mecha]] from the [[Macross]] series.

The [b]YF-29 Durandal[/b] is an advanced prototype of the [[VF-25]] Messiah variable fighter that first appeared in the [[Macross Frontier: Sayonara No Tsubasa]] animated movie from 2011. Its next animated appearance is in the [[Macross Delta: Zettai Live!!!!!!]] animated movie from 2021.

Features include [[canards]] and forward-swept wings with built-in extra boosters. Only one exists and is in use by the [[S.M.S.]] company. It is piloted by [[Saotome Alto]], and its color scheme is red and white.

Several years later, [[Maximilian Jenius]] piloted a YF-29, which is painted in his signature blue and white color scheme. 

In [[real life]] it was designed by [[Kawamori Shouji]].

title: space:_1999
body:
[b]Space: 1999[/b] is a 70s British [[science fiction]] TV series that ran for two seasons and originally aired from 1975 to 1977. 

Space: 1999 is the last in a long line of Sci-Fi series that Gerry and Sylvia Anderson produced as a working partnership, beginning with Supercar in the early Sixties and including the famed marionette fantasy series Stingray, Fireball XL5, [[Thunderbirds (series)|]], Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons, Joe 90 and The Secret Service, as well as the live-action [[alien]] invasion drama [[UFO (copyright)|]]. 

Space: 1999 owes much of the visual design to pre-production work for the never made second series of UFO, which would have been set primarily on the Moon and featured a more extensive Moonbase. Space: 1999 also drew a great deal of visual inspiration (and technical expertise) from the Stanley Kubrick film [[2001 A Space Odyssey]]. The programme's special effects director Brian Johnson had previously worked on both Thunderbirds (as Brian Johncock) and 2001. Many members of the special effects staff also worked in the movie [[Alien (1979)|]] and the [[Star Wars]] films some years later. 

The series was very famous in Japan, where it influenced the designs and look of [[macross|several Sci-Fi anime shows]] released during the following years.

h4. See also

* [[Eagle Transporter]]

title: kirby_and_the_rainbow_curse
body:
The sole [[kirby_(series)|Kirby]] game for the Nintendo [[Wii U]], and a spiritual sequel to [[Kirby Canvas Curse]]. Unlike the predecessor, this game forgoes [[copy_ability|copy abilities]] in favor of methodical puzzle solving and occasional transformations.

Kirby and friends were having fun in a clay-ful Dream Land one day. Suddenly a portal opens up! Out comes a magical force that sucks away all the color from Dream Land. Luckily, [[Bandana Waddle Dee]] fends off the new invader before it could defeat our puffy hero. Together with Bandana Waddle Dee and a paintbrush fairy named [[Elline (kirby)|]], Kirby sets out to bring color back to his world!

title: denpa_onna_to_seishun_otoko
body:
[b]Denpa Onna to Seishun Otoko[/b] (電波女と青春男, transl. [i]Ground Control to Psychoelectric Girl[/i]) is a 2009-2011 light novel series written by Iruma Hitoma and illustrated by [[Buriki]], with a manga adaptation illustrated by [[Yamane Masato]] and serialized in ASCII Media Works' [i]Dengeki G's Magazine[/i], and 2011 anime adaptation by [[SHAFT (company)|]].

Due to his parents' overseas work, [[Niwa Makoto]] moves to the city to live with his 39-year-old aunt [[Touwa Meme]]. The boy, who expected to live a dream life with a harem, is instead confronted with a hitherto unknown relative: Meme's daughter [[Touwa Erio|Erio]], a strange recluse with a fascination for aliens. Makoto has since been trying to help her open up, even as he gets to know more about his cousin.

title: uchiage_hanabi_shita_kara_miru_ka?_yoko_kara_miru_ka?
body:
Literally [i]Fireworks, Should We See Them From the Bottom or the Side?[/i]. A 1993 made-for-television live action film by Iwai Shunji. The story focused on a group of students going out to watch the fireworks, while another boy in their group, Norimichi, gets called to run away with fellow schoolmate and secret crush [[oikawa_nazuna|Nazuna]].

The film was given an animated remake in 2017 by [[SHAFT (company)|]], directed by Shinbo Akiyuki and Takeuchi Noboyuki. DAOKO was the singer for the theme "Uchiage Hanabi". [[Fuugetsu Makoto]] adapted the film into a manga in June of the same year. Localized in English as [i]Fireworks[/i].

title: japanese_regalia
body:
The Imperial Regalia of Japan (三種の神器 Sanshu no Jingi / Mikusa no Kandakara), also known as the Three Sacred Treasures of Japan, consist of the [[sword_of_kusanagi|sword Kusanagi]] (草薙劍 Kusanagi no Tsurugi), the mirror Yata no Kagami (八咫鏡), and the jewel Yasakani no Magatama (八尺瓊曲玉). The regalia represent the three primary virtues: valor (the sword), wisdom (the mirror), and benevolence (the jewel).

Due to the legendary status of these items, their locations or appearance are not confirmed, but it is commonly thought that the sword is located at Atsuta Shrine in Nagoya, the jewel is located at Kōkyo (the Imperial Palace) in Tōkyō, and the mirror is located in the Ise Grand Shrine in Mie Prefecture.

h4. External link
* "Wikipedia:Imperial Regalia of Japan":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_Regalia_of_Japan

title: skull_servant
body:
Japanese name: ワイト (Wight)
English name: Skull Servant

An [[undead]] [[skeleton]] [[duel monster]] from [[Yu-Gi-Oh!]].

He is treated as a [[meme]] character within the Yu-Gi-Oh! community, initially due to his awful stats and lack of support, which later prompted [[Konami]] to create a joke archtypes around him. Also gained popularity outsides of the community due to his appearance in the [[Jaguarman Series]].

Note that this tag also covers "King of the Skull Servants" ("Wightking" in Japanese), a much stronger variant of this monster who is otherwise identical to the original Skull Servant in appearance.

h4.External links

title: demon_back_(baki)
body:
A peculiar [[fighting stance]] exclusive to [[Hanma Yujiro]] and his son [[Hanma Baki]] from [[Grappler Baki]], to which they are used to unleash their full strength. The stance is named such due to the back muscles of the user would form into the shape of a "Demon's face" when it is used.

The stance consists of the user [[flexing]] their muscles with an [[outstretched arms]] and [[claw pose|clawed hands]] above the user's head level. In doing so, the user's [[torn shirt|shirt will be torn up]] due to muscle expansion for dramatic effect.

title: receding_hairline
body:
A receding hairline refers to the thinning or loss of hair on the scalp, particularly at the front and top of the scalp, starting at the temple. It is a disorder that can be caused by many different factors and is more common in men than women.

It is typically caused by genetics, aging related to male pattern hair loss, stress and hormonal changes (aka testosterone).

* !post #7443284

title: g-lucifer
body:
[b]VGMM-Gf10 Gundam G-Lucifer[/b]

A prototype [[mobile_suit|MS]] developed by the G-IT Laboratory. It is named a "Gundam" despite its odd appearance, somewhat resembling the old [[Qubeley]]. 

It possesses Skirt Funnels, which can be either controlled by its pilot or by a dedicated copilot, [spoilers]and the deadly [[Moonlight Butterfly (gundam)|]] System that can deploy destructive nanomachines. The secret system means it is either a prototype of the [[Turn A Gundam (mobile suit)|∀ Gundam]] and [[Turn X]] or the units' successor.[/spoilers] 

It was piloted by [[Raraiya Monday|Raraiya Akparl]] and [[Noredo Nug]] as they chose to fight against the Capital Army and Towasanga forces and restore peace on Earth.

title: turn_x
body:
The main antagonist [[mecha]] from the [[Turn A Gundam]] anime series from 1999.

Is notable because it was designed by the legendary American [[science fiction]] film designer [[Syd Mead]]. 

The [b]CONCEPT-X 6-1-2 Turn X[/b] was originally going to be the hero mecha of the show, but series director [[Tomino Yoshiyuki]] coinsidered the design too "un-Gundamish", so he chose the design as the antagonist robot and made Syd Mead develop [[turn_a_gundam_(mobile_suit)|another design]] (which was also kinda "un-Gundamish" in the end...).

Although it is also equipped with the [[Moonlight Butterfly (gundam)|]] super weapon, the Turn X is the second strongest Mobile Suit in the entire franchise due to the fact that the Turn A Gundam defeated it not once, but twice.

title: moonlight_butterfly_(gundam)
body:
The most dangerous weapon of both the [[turn_a_gundam_(mobile_suit)|Turn A Gundam]] and the [[Turn X]] [[mecha]] from the [[Turn A Gundam]] anime series - [spoiler]as well as the [[G-Lucifer]] from [[Gundam G no Reconguista]].[/spoiler] These are strange, colorful butterfly wings made of pure energy that emit from the Turn units when the attack is active. It is said that the attack has three requirements, the nanomachines, the energy to use them, and finally the program to activate it. 

At full power, the [b]Moonlight Butterfly[/b] can cover a wide range (from [[Earth (planet)|]] to [[Jupiter (planet)|]]), while turning most if not all technologies into silicon dioxide (sand). Lastly, the Moonlight Butterfly can be used as a defense of sorts as it can easily defend against both beam and physical attacks.

To date, it is still the most powerful [[Gundam]] super weapon in the entire franchise.

She is visually identifiable for being an [[elf]], her [[very long hair|very long]] [[white hair]] with a large [[red]] [[hair ribbon|ribbon in it]], [[blue eyes]], fair-sized [[breasts]], and usually wearing an elaborate [[slave]] collar.  

Her usual attire (besides the collar and ribbon) are a [[white dress|white full-length dress]] or a blue [[maid]] outfit.

title: dissidia_012_final_fantasy
body:
Full title:  [b][i]DISSIDIA 012[duodecim] FINAL FANTASY[/i][/b]

A 2011 [[PlayStation Portable]] action-RPG video game by [[Square Enix]], a spinoff to the [[Final Fantasy]] series, and [spoiler]prequel[/spoiler] to [i][[Dissidia Final Fantasy]][/i].
Like its predecessor, [i]Dissidia 012[/i] features various playable heroes and villains from the mainstream series fighting on behalf of either [[Cosmos (dff)|]], goddess of harmony, or [[Chaos (dff)|]], god of discord, but with new characters, new gameplay mechanics, and a new story, set during the [spoiler]twelfth cycle of the endless battle between Cosmos and Chaos[/spoiler].

h4. Playable Characters

h5. Returning Characters

* The [[Warrior of Light (ff1)|]] and [[Garland (ff1)|]] from [i][[final_fantasy_i|FFI]][/i]
* [[Firion]] and [[Emperor (ff2)|The Emperor]] from [i][[final_fantasy_ii|FFII]][/i]
* The [[Onion Knight]] and [[Cloud of Darkness]] from [i][[final_fantasy_iii|FFIII]][/i]
* [[Cecil Harvey]] and [[Golbez]] from [i][[final_fantasy_iv|FFIV]][/i]

title: wise_mystical_tree_(meme)
body:
Also known as "If You're Over 25 and Own a Computer, This Game Is a Must-Have", and "Must-Play Tree", refers to clickbait ads for several browser games that feature a human-faced [[tree]] character and a [[knight]] [[kneeling]] in front of it, with the text often claiming that if you're above a certain age and own a computer, then you must try the game. It gained popularity as a video caption and remix format, and have often been combined with the composition "Secunda" from the [[the elder scrolls v: skyrim|Skyrim]] soundtrack.

h4. External links
* "KnowYourMeme":https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/wise-mystical-tree-if-youre-over-25-and-own-a-computer-this-game-is-a-must-have

title: colored_pencil_(medium)
body:
[[Traditional media|Traditional]] art created using colored pencils.

Colored pencils are characterized by their pigmented, usually wax-based, core. Also known as "pencil crayons", these come in several different qualities; from the poor and uneven Crayola offering to the popular Prismacolour and the high-dollar Pablos.

title: resident_evil_7:_biohazard
body:
[i][b]Resident Evil 7: Biohazard[/b][/i] is a part of the Resident Evil series was released  in January 2017.

It is the first game in the series to use a first person mode, and supports PlayStation VR, and notable for bringing the franchise back to the survival horror genre.

h4.Story

The story follows Ethan Winters as he searches for his wife Mia, which leads him to a derelict plantation inhabited by the Baker family.

title: eveline
body:
The main antagonist of [[Resident Evil 7: Biohazard]], her existence is somewhat of a spoiler in itself.

[spoilers]Eveline is a bioweapon engineered to harness a special 'mold' which she can use to influence and control others, as well as to construct bipedal zombie-like monsters. She presents herself in hallucinations in her youthful form, with [[black hair]] and a [[black dress]], which fan art of her usually depicts her in. Her true body, however, has deteriorated into that of an old woman due to accelerated aging. [/spoilers]

title: toushin_toshi_girls_gift
body:
A remake of [[Toushin Toshi II]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]], featuring updated graphics, redesigned characters, and small adjustments to the story.

Unlike the original game, Girls Gift does not contain any explicit nudity or sexual content, making it one of the few [[Alicesoft]] games not to feature said content.

title: serabarla_f
body:
A minor NPC in [[Toushin Toshi II]], and a boss character in its remake, [[Toushin Toshi Girls Gift]].

In the original game, Serabarla F is a "manager [[angel]]" who possesses the Soul Death Wave Motion Gun, a weapon capable of erasing the very existence of anyone it targets. Her character is altered in the remake, where she is much younger than her original counterpart, though she still has the Soul Death Wave Motion Gun. She also now possesses the epithet "Cannon Angel."

In the original game, Serabarla F's design includes [[brown hair]], [[brown eyes]], a [[blue dress]] with a [[white apron]], and a pair of [[angel wings]]. Her altered design in Girls Gift retains many of these features, except Serabarla herself is significantly younger.

title: pretty_rhythm
body:
Pretty Rhythm is a Japanese Taito Type X2 arcade game by Takara Tomy. It has been adapted into a manga series by Mari Asabuki. An anime adaptation by Tatsunoko Production, titled [[pretty_rhythm_aurora dream|Pretty Rhythm: Aurora Dream]], aired in Japan between April 2011 and March 2012. This was followed by a sequel, [[pretty_rhythm_dear_my_future|Pretty Rhythm: Dear My Future]], which aired between April 2012 and March 2013. A third series, [[pretty rhythm rainbow live|Pretty Rhythm: Rainbow Live]], began airing from April 6, 2013.

The series focuses on the creation and management of idols that perform in Prism Shows, a form of entertainment that combines singing, performance art, and figure skating.

The series has an alternate continuity spinoff franchise known as [[PriPara]], and another separate continuity called [[Kiratto Pri chan]]. All three are collectively under the [i][[pretty series|Pretty]][/i] metafranchise label.

A [[male_focus|male-focused]] spinoff movie series called [i][[King of Prism]][/i] launched in 2016. [i][[King of Prism by Prettyrhythm]][/i] premiered in January 2016, starring [[Hayami Hiro]], [[Mihama Kouji]], and [[Nishina Kazuki]] as the main characters, with sequel films following in 2017 and 2019.

She has [[short hair|short]] [[black hair]] and [[heterochromia]] with [[blue eyes|blue]] and [[brown eyes]]. Her default outfit consists of a [[purple sweater]] with [[white pants]] and [[black footwear|black]] [[sneakers]].

Rhapsody is voiced by [[Xanthe Huynh]]. Like fellow Mobile-exclusive legend [[Fade (apex legends)|]], Respawn has not announced any plans to bring her to the main game following the Mobile port's closure.

title: tengen_toppa_gurren_lagann
body:
A 2007 original [[super robot]] [[mecha]] anime series animated by [[Gainax]] and co-produced by [[Aniplex]] and [[Konami]]. Best known for its over-the-top plot, action sequence, along with its ridiculously huge mecha.

h4. Plot summary

In the distant future, people build their homes and raise domestic animals in subterranean caverns. As a result, they live in fear of the occasional earthquake and cave-in, and have been for hundreds of years. Jeeha is one such village.

One day, a boy named [[Simon (ttgl)|]] happens to find a small, shiny drill while digging to expand the village. At the same time, [[Kamina (ttgl)|]], a guy who believes that there is another land above the village, persuades a gangster to break through the ceiling in order to leave the cavern. Suddenly, an earthquake occurs and the ceiling collapses, followed by a big [[robot]] breaking through the ceiling.

Kamina is now sure that there is a world above them. Recklessly, he begins to fight against the robot. At that moment, another person appears from the land above. It is a girl by the name of [[Yoko Littner|Yoko]]. With a [[rifle]] in hand, she had been tracking the robot. However, all she could do was distract it. Then, Simon shows what he had found to Kamina and Yoko. It's a mysterious robot whose head is also its body.

title: mobile_armor
body:
A type of [[mecha]] from the [[Gundam]] series, mobile armors are typically massive, heavily destructive, usually non-humanoid units that dwarf the average [[mobile suit]]. While generally much more sluggish than mobile suit, they are typically designed as a weapon of mass destruction (often housing a single mega beam particle cannon in its center), with some even capable of defeating an entire spaceship fleet on its own.

The term is also sometimes used to refer to the alternate forms of certain transforming mobile suits, including the [[Baund Doc]] and [[Methuss]].

Mobile armors are depicted fairly consistently throughout the franchise's AU series. The only major exception to this is [[Gundam SEED]], in which the majority of the mobile armors seen are more akin to [[starfighter|starfighters]].

title: hashmal_(mobile_armor)
body:
[b]??????? Hashmal[/b]

One of the ancient [[mobile armor]]s, unmanned weapons of mass destruction that once nearly wiped out humanity. It was disabled and buried in Mars until Tekkadan found its carcass, at which point the foolish actions of [[Iok Kujan]] awakened the ferocious monster. The ensuing battle killed hundreds and required [[Mikazuki Augus]] to sacrifice the movement of his entire right side and almost destroy the [[Gundam Barbatos Lupus]] in order to stop the rampaging beast.

title: big_zam
body:
A fictional [[mobile armor]] [[walker (robot)|]] [[mecha]] from the [[Gundam]] franchise. It first appeared in the [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] TV series from 1979.

The [b]MA-08 Big Zam[/b] is a Principality of [[Zeon]] heavy walker designed as a prototype anti-warship and anti-fortress [[mobile armor]].

It is huge in size with wide body and no arms, and is armed with a very powerful large mega-particle [[beam cannon]].

It is the mecha of choice for [[Dozle Zabi]].

title: our_wonderland
body:
[b]Our Wonderland[/b] is a freeware horror romance visual novel by [i]Carrot Patch Games[/i] from 2021 to 2024.

h4. Story

Eleven-year-old Iggy wasn’t sure what he was expecting when he dragged his friends out to the woods to attempt a strange ritual from a book he found in the dumpster at school, but his wildest imagination couldn’t have prepared him for the land of wonder and magic that awaited them at the bottom of that old willow tree.

Now, however, it’s twenty years later, and he and his friends are past the age of make-believe. The wonderland of their youth has become nothing more than a far-off dream—until one night, Bucks and her newborn daughter disappear without a trace. Soon, Iggy and his friends find themselves pulled back into that world of childish glee. Only their wishes and desires aren’t so innocent anymore, and the world has twisted itself into a land of horror and depravity that’s scarcely recognizable.

title: marble_(stone)
body:
Marble is a metamorphic rock (rock transformed by heat and pressure) created from sedimentary carbonate rocks, particularly limestone or dolomite rock.  It can take on a high polish and is commonly used in architecture and sculpture.

Pure white marble is the result of metamorphism of a very pure (silicate-poor) limestone or dolomite. The characteristic swirls and veins of many colored marble varieties are usually due to various mineral impurities such as clay, silt, sand, iron oxides, or chert which were originally present as grains or layers in the limestone.

title: ushba_tesoro_(racehorse)
body:
[tn]Named after "a mountain in the Caucasus":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ushba] + Kanmei (Spanish or Italian: "Treasure". Pronounciation implies Spanish.)[/tn]

[[Real life]] racehorse. Sired by [[Orfevre (racehorse)|]] and foaled by Millefeui Attach. Two time winner of the Tokyo Daishoten, and the winner of the 2023 Dubai World Cup.

A late bloomer due to being misplaced on turf, he very rapidly became Japan's top runner on dirt. He became Japan's highest earning racehorse not only due to his wins at the Tokyo Daishoten and at the Dubai World Cup, but also for his second places at the Saudi Cup and at his second Dubai World Cup, which are some of the races with the richest purses in the world, dethroning [[Equinox (racehorse)|]] from the spot.

Despite being a brilliant runner, he is actually very lazy in training.

title: sleggar_law
body:
A fictional character from the [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] science fiction and [[mecha]] anime TV series from 1979.

[b]Sleggar Law[/b] is a womanizing and alcoholic veteran [[Earth Federation Space Forces]] [[soldier]] and [[pilot]] who serves as [[teacher|senpai]] to most of the young crew of the [[White Base]]. [spoilers]Sleggar dies in [[battle]] with [[Zeon]] forces when his [[Core Booster]] is crushed by (and crashes at) the [[Big Zam]] during a daring final attack on the gigantic machine.[/spoilers]

In [[real life]] Sleggar served as inspiration for the character of [[Roy Focker]] from [[Choujikuu Yousai Macross]] (1982)[spoiler], who has a similar fate[/spoiler].

title: lord_peach
body:
[[Princess Peach]] transformed into a [[Bowser]] look-alike, in a [[role reversal]] on the [[Bowsette]] concept.

There is no set transformation item: Bowser-inspired [[Super Crown]], [[spiked shell]], [[spiked collar]], [[mushroom]]…

Main depictions include:
* Bowser's body, retaining Peach's pink coat (as [[pink_skin|skin]] and/or [[shell]] color), [[blonde hair]], [[blue eyes]], blue [[jewelry]] and [[white gloves]].
* Same, but the head in Bowser's colors.
* [[Bishounen]] human with a [[crown]], [[pointy ears]] and Bowser's [[red hair]], [[spiked shell]] and sometimes [[spiked bracelet]]s.

Tag [[genderswap (ftm)]] if male, even the transform is due to a Super crown analog.

Alternate names are "Peacher", "Peachzer", and "Peazer".

title: project_diva_(series)
body:
h4. SEGA feat. HATSUNE MIKU Project

h6. 初音ミク -Project DIVA-

A series of Rhythm Action games published by [[SEGA]] featuring [[Hatsune Miku]] and her fellow Crypton [[Vocaloid]]s. These games were released on the [[PlayStation Portable]], [[Playstation Vita]], and [[Playstation 3]].

Project DIVA is a simple rhythm game where you tap/hold buttons corresponding to icons on the screen while listening to various Vocaloid songs. You can dress each Vocaloid in unique [[list_of_project_diva_modules|Modules]] (costumes) to dance in during each song, which you must unlock by clearing different conditions depending on the module. When not playing the rhythm games, you can view songs in PV mode, or interact with the Vocaloids themselves in the DIVA Room.

Use of this tag alone is allowed for images that reference Project DIVA in some way, but do not depict modules from any of the games. Please do not include the {{Vocaloid}} tag if the image does not include any Vocaloid characters in it.

h6.Examples:
* post #819162 and post #1244598, resembles/parodies the game's interface or rhythm game icons
* post #912808, a controller designed specifically for Project DIVA
* post #1014359, parodies or use of the Project DIVA logo/name

h5.Games
* [[project diva|Hatsune Miku -Project DIVA-]]
* [[project diva 2nd|Hatsune Miku -Project DIVA- 2nd]]
* [[project diva extend|Hatsune Miku -Project DIVA- extend]]
* [[project diva f|Hatsune Miku -Project DIVA- f/F]]
* [[project diva f 2nd|Hatsune Miku -Project DIVA- F2nd]]
* [[project diva x|Hatsune Miku -Project DIVA- X]]

title: pokemon_sm_(anime)
body:
The sixth series of the [[pokemon (anime)|Pokémon anime]] and is based on the events of the Generation VII core series Pokémon games. It follows [[pokemon xy (anime)|Pokémon the Series: XY]] and was succeeded by [[pokemon journeys|Pokémon Journeys: The Series]]. It ran from November 17, 2016 to November 3, 2019 in Japan and from May 12, 2017 to March 7, 2020 in the United States.

In this series, [[Ash Ketchum]] travels to the tropical region of Alola, accompanied by his partner [[Pikachu]]. Unlike in the five previous series, however, Ash doesn't travel through the region. Instead, he becomes a student at the Pokémon School on [[Melemele Island]], where he meets his new classmates [[Lana (pokemon)|]], [[Lillie (pokemon)|]], [[Mallow (pokemon)|]], [[Sophocles (pokemon)|]], and [[Kiawe (pokemon)|]]. After receiving a [[Z-Ring]] from the Legendary guardian deity [[Tapu Koko]], Ash decides to take on the Alolan island challenge to obtain new [[Z-Crystal]]s and master various [[Z-Move]]s.

title: sleepwalking
body:
Also known as somnambulism or noctambulism, it is a phenomenon of combined [[sleeping|sleep]] and wakefulness.

It is classified as a sleep disorder belonging to the parasomnia family. It occurs during slow wave stage of [[sleeping|sleep]], in a state of low consciousness, with performance of activities that are usually done during a state of waking consciousness. 

These activities can be as benign as [[talking]], [[sitting]] up in bed, [[walking]] to a [[bathroom]], [[eating]], and [[cleaning]], or as hazardous as [[cooking]], driving a [[motor vehicle]], and [[violence|violent gestures]].

The typical popular culture depiction may be a [[zombie pose]].

title: cryptid
body:
A cryptid refers to an animal (or monster or creature) whose existence is unsubstantiated by mainstream science. They are the subjects of the pseudoscience of cryptozoology.

The favored term in Japan for cryptids is "Unindentified Mysterious Animal" or "UMA", displaying the parallels with "[[UFO]]" (and the parallels of cryptozoology and ufology) as well as a source of [[horse]] jokes, particularly in [[Umamusume]] circles as actual horses do not exist in the setting where famous race horses are turned in to girls.

[[Kemono Friends]] uses the term "UMA" to designate friends based on cryptids, animal [[traditional youkai]] and other mythical and folkloral creatures, fictional animal characters, the [[Tachikoma]] (and other [[Ghost in the Shell]] robot Friends) and hybrids of any of the above with real animals.

title: samsung_galaxy_(league_of_legends)
body:
[b]Samsung Galaxy[/b] was a Korean a professional gaming team based in South Korea, part of KeSPA. The organization previously sponsored two sister teams, Samsung White and Samsung Blue. Founded in 2005, its StarCraft division, Samsung KHAN, counts ex-Team WE coach Lee Seong-eun (firebathero) among the stars that have been on its roster.

The team won League of Legends 2017 World Championships after defeating [[t1 (esports)|SK Telecom T1]] 3-0 in Finals. Later however, Samsung announced that they would no longer sponsor anymore teams in professional play and the team was then obtained by the Chinese Company KSV, thus forming [b]KSV eSports[/b] and then rebranding to [b]Geneneration Gaming[/b] also known as [b]Gen.G[/b]

Layla is confirmed to not be Japanese, but her ethnicity is currently still unrevealed, although she is from Dubai. [b]Kono Yubi Tomare[/b] (Japanese, meaning [i]Stay With This Finger[/i]), [b]Follow Me[/b] (English)[b] 날따름[/b](Korean)

Follow Me is a [i][[pokemon|Pokémon]][/i] move.

When a Pokémon uses Follow Me, any moves used by the opponent(s) are forced to target it (rather than other intended targets).

In battle animation, a floating white glove pointing up usually appears close to the user. This is a reference to the Japanese name of this move.

h5. Pokémon World Championship

Some posts involve a [[Pachirisu]] using Follow Me (post #1793246, post #3555002, etc.). They are usually about [[Se Jun Park]]'s Pachirisu, which was a member of his winning team in the [[Video Game Championships 2014|Pokémon VGC World Championship 2014]].

title: yuan_xiu
body:
[b]Emperor Xiaowu[/b], last emperor of the proto-mongolic Xiangbei led [b]Northern Wei[/b]. He is at times known as Emperor Chu (出帝, "the emperor who fled").

 After the general Gao Huan rebelled against and defeated the clan of the deceased paramount general Erzhu Rong in 532, he made Emperor Xiaowu emperor. Despite Gao's making him emperor, however, Emperor Xiaowu tried strenuously to free himself from Gao's control, and in 534, he, aligning with the general Yuwen Tai, formally broke with Gao. When Gao advanced south to try to again take control of the imperial government, Emperor Xiaowu fled to Yuwen's territory, leading to Northern Wei's division into two (as Gao then made Yuan Shanjian (Emperor Xiaojing of Eastern Wei) the heir apparent, establishing Eastern Wei). Emperor Xiaowu's relationship with Yuwen, however, soon deteriorated over Yuwen's refusal to condone his incestuous relationships with his cousins, and around the new year 535, Yuwen poisoned him to death. Emperor Xiaowu's successor, Yuan Baoju (Emperor Wen of Western Wei), is typically regarded, then, as the first emperor of Western Wei, formalizing the division of the empire.

title: pearl_(splatoon)
body:
[[Splatoon 2]] character. Named [b]Hime[/b] in the Japanese version. She is an [[Inkling]].

She is part of the band Off The Hook (Tentacles in the Japanese version) with [[Marina (splatoon)|]], which has its own television show.

Her Japanese name comes from the word for the "Northern pygmy squid":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idiosepius_paradoxus (ヒメイカ [i]Hime-ika[/i]). As revealed in Octotune's album booklet, her full name in Japanese is [b]Hime Houzuki[/b].

In her default costume & appearance she wears a [[white dress]], [[pink pantyhose]], black [[fingerless gloves]], white [[shoes]] and a [[crown]]. She has [[thick eyebrows]] and a [[mole under mouth|mole under her mouth]]. She has white / yellow [[star-shaped pupils]]. title: scylla
body:
A type of [[monster girl]] resembling a sea [[octopus]], most commonly taking the form in Japanese works of a human upper torso and [[tentacles]] for legs.  

Named after a Greek mythological monster that has had many varying descriptions over the centuries.  One later mythological version of the scylla was more or less a [[mermaid]] whose serpentine-like lower half was surrounded by snapping dog heads. For that character, use [[scylla (mythology)]] instead.

Other names associated with octopus girls are Cecaelia and Dagon.

h4. Notable Scyllas

title: suspenders
body:
Suspenders or Galluses, known as Braces in British English, are elastic fabric straps worn over the shoulders to hold up trousers. The entire strap of braces may be elasticated, or only at attachment ends, with the most of the straps being of woven cloth with either a X-Back or Y-back crosspatch and leather end tabs. Braces typically attach to trousers with clips or, less commonly nowadays, with buttons. In British English the term suspenders or suspender belt refers to a [[garter belt]], used to hold up [[thighhighs|stockings]].

h4. See also

* [[garter belt]]

title: mochizuki_chiyome_(fate)
body:
Assassin-class servant in [i][[Fate/Grand Order]][/i]. A legendary founder of the first kunoichi order of her era, she also served as a miko of Orochi, hence her connection to [[Shuten Douji (fate)|Shuten-douji]] (who is depicted in Fate/Grand Order as Orochi's daughter).

Usually wears only a [[black ribbon]] with [[fishnets]] (where a part of the ribbon covers her right eye as an [[eyepatch]]), and wields a [[kunai]]. Has [[very long hair|very long]] [[black hair]] and [[purple eyes]]. Often some of her hair [[hair over one eye|covers her right eye]] too. Gains a kunoichi and miko outfit as she ascends, revealing that her covered eye is yellow and has a serpentine pupil, the mark of her priesthood serving Orochi.

[b]Character Design[/b]: [[Hiroyama Hiroshi]]

title: yukkuri_abuse
body:
Deformed characters associated with the [[yukkuri shiteitte ne]] meme being mutilated, tortured or killed. Essentially a form of [[guro]]. Due to their resemblance to a [[manjuu]], they are often shown to contain [[red bean paste]] instead of blood and viscera.

[b]Images to which this tag would apply are prohibited on Danbooru[/b].

However, images where yukkuri are mistreated with minimal detail (insufficient for the [[ryona]] or [[guro]] tag to be applied if they were human with human blood/organs) are permitted, particularly when the abuse is not the focus of the image or is presented in a slapstick context. Ask on the forums before uploading them if you are unsure.

Here are some examples of images that contain a permissible level of yukkuri mistreatment, and are allowed on Danbooru:
* !post #553579
* !post #688729
* !post #922420
* !post #1218361

Do not tag images similar to these with [[yukkuri abuse]].

body:
The traditional, military style [[school uniform]] for male students in middle schools and high schools in Japan, usually in either black or navy. 

The top has a standing collar buttoning down from top-to-bottom. Pants are straight leg and a black or dark-colored belt is worn with them.

Frequently seen in many anime male protagonists.

title: urameshiya
body:
うらめしや～！

Literally: "I hate you!" or "I envy your life!" A phrase often said by youkai, such as ghosts or possessed objects (like the [[karakasa obake]]), to express envy towards humans, whose place in the Six Realms of Buddhist belief affords them less suffering. It's an old phrasing not commonly used in modern Japanese and as a result it's often translated as "Boo!" 

[[Tatara Kogasa]] of [[Touhou|Touhou Project]] used the phrase in her first appearance in [[Undefined Fantastic Object]] and often uses it in fan works.

This tag should only be used when a character can be seen saying the phrase.

title: lord_of_the_mysteries
body:
A Chinese trilogy web-novel story written by Cuttlefish That Loves Diving. First part is composed of 8 volumes. Second book, [[Circle of Inevitability]], was officially released on 4th of March.  The "web comic adaption":https://www.webnovel.com/comic/lord-of-the-mysteries_15896372906358001 was translated but cancelled later on. 

There was an "anime announcement":[https://www.weibo.com/6340649546/KstWn6j5z?pagetype=profilefeed] and the "release date trailer":[https://www.weibo.com/6340649546/NdCONkPPR?pagetype=profilefeed] confirm it for 2025.

There is a "game announcement":[https://weibo.com/7344384861/MriAo7WQy] by the name of "Code Name Mystery":[https://lotm.tzxxx.com/?mark_id=999_reallog_mark_ad%3A999%7CWeiboADNatural&continueFlag=8f75ea3c60f02d7aee7fc531bc0ee944] that includes pre-registration for interested people.

h4. Synopsis

In the waves of steam and machinery, who could achieve extraordinary? In the fogs of history and darkness, who was whispering? I woke up from the realm of mysteries and opened my eyes to the world.

Firearms, cannons, battleships, airships, and difference machines. Potions, divination, curses, hanged-man, and sealed artifacts… The lights shone brightly, yet the secrets of the world were never far away. This was a legend of the “fool”.

title: meikei_yell_(racehorse)
body:
Real Life Japanese Thoroughbred racehorse. Sired by Mikki Isle and foaled by Shiroinger (By Harbinger and Yukichan). A non-white horse from the Shirayukihime lineage of white horses, she is best known for her difficult temper as well as her familial relationship with [[Sodashi (racehorse)|]]. Adding to her infamy is that her main jockey is [[Ikezoe Ken'ichi]], best known for racing on particularly difficult horses.

Although she was a solid sprinter with 3 G2s, she never won any G1s due to her own moodiness and temper, her results even being all-or-nothing (7 victories, no podiums and 5 placements - all G1 races - in 20 races). She instead ended up being the spectator of Sodashi and [[Mama Cocha (racehorse)|]]'s own G1s. She retired after the 2024 Takamatsunomiya Kinen.

title: honda_motocompo
body:
A collapsible [[minibike]] designed by Honda to fit into the trunk of subcompact [[car|cars]]. It was manufactured from 1981-1983, and is probably best known for being featured in [[Fujishima Kousuke|Fujishima Kousuke's]] [[Taiho Shichauzo]] anime and manga series.

Honda announced in 2023 the release of an all-electric "e-scooter" based on the Motocompo called the [[Honda Motocompacto|Motocompacto]].

title: mark_hamill
body:
[b]Mark Richard Hamill[/b] (b. September 25, 1951)

American actor and [[voice actor]].

Became famous for portraying the character of [[Luke Skywalker]] in the [[Star Wars]] [[science fiction|space opera]] movie franchise in his youth during the 70s and 80s, a role he returned to play during the new sequel trilogy of films (and net series) produced by [[Disney]].

Also a [[otaku|notable comic book collector]] and accomplished voice actor, quite popular for his role as the crazy [[DC comics]] villain [[Joker (dc)|]] in many animated series, movies and video games.

body:
The biological father of [[Liquid Snake]], [[Solidus Snake]], and [[Solid Snake]]. title: lace
body:
Clothing made entirely of lace. Lace is a delicate fabric, usually colored white, containing intricate web-like patterns.

[[Frills]] may be made of lace, but many are not lace, and not all lace is frilled. [[Lace]] is commonly misused to indicate [[frills]], so be careful with this tag.

Lace is often used for decorative [[lace trim]]. However, do not use the [[lace]] tag for clothing that simply has [[lace trim]]. [[Lace]] is for clothing that is completely made of lace.

title: jidaigeki
body:
A [[Japan]]ese period drama, generally set during the Heian (794–1185 CE), Sengoku (1467–1615 CE), Edo (1603–1868 CE), or Early Meiji eras of Japanese history.

Generally features [[samurai]] (or [[ronin]]) as main characters, with feudal lords, shoguns, ninjas, peasants, craftsmen and merchants also playing important parts. Often focuses on intense sword-fights between samurai and other sword-wielding characters.

Characters will usually dress in the period-appropriate attire in such works. Some characters (often the more 'regal' or 'authoritative' ones) will speak in a faux "antiquated stage Japanese", analogous to using "thees and thous" and other 'Shakespearisms' in an English work.

Drawn works set in a jidaigeki setting will often feature a [[sumi-e]] "ink wash" aesthetic or other elements of traditional Japanese art.

For tagging purposes, any post that depicts a visibly "Medieval Japanese" setting generally counts. Consider this the Japanese culture equivalent of the [[Medieval]] tag. Avoid tagging [[Touhou]] works with this tag, or other mixed fantastical/sci-fi settings, unless they have the distinct "jidaigeki" feel. 

(This may be hard to quantify, but generally, if it feels like a "samurai period piece film", then it counts, even if it's a mixed setting.)

h4. Tag usage notes
* Tag jidaigeki for posts that feature a visibly Japanese 'Medieval' theme.
** Especially if it focuses on samurai and feudal lords/shoguns, analogous to knights and lords for Western [[Medieval]] works.
* Avoid tagging jidaigeki for mixed settings unless one is  sure that it qualifies.
* Avoid tagging jidaigeki for settings that have a central focus on fantastical or 'magical' elements, even if set in the appropriate era.
** Generally these will focus on gods, magic, youkai and the like. 
** e.g. [[Ookami (game)|Ōkami]] (it is also set in prehistoric Japan instead of 'medieval' Japan.)
** The analogy is like [[medieval]] vs. [[fantasy]]. There is some overlap, and some posts may qualify for both. Likewise, some overtly fantastical or 'magical' settings may also [i]feel[/i] jidaigeki if there is significant focus on samurai characters (or feudal lords, or "the common people").
* [[Ninja]]s by themselves generally do not count for jidaigeki. 

h4. Notable series

* [[Kozure Ookami]] [tn]Edo period[/tn]
* [[Vagabond]] [tn]Edo period[/tn]
* [[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]] [tn]Sengoku period, with some fantastical and steampunk elements[/tn]
* [[Rurouni Kenshin]] [tn]Early Meiji period[/tn]

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Jidaigeki":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jidaigeki]

title: astral_express_(honkai:_star_rail)
body:
The Astral Express is a large [[train]] that serves as one of the main settings of [[Honkai: Star Rail]] operated by the Nameless. It is powered by Akivili, the Aeon of the Trailblazer.

In the past, the Astral Express was first bestowed by Akivili. Shortly after the fall of the Aeon, the Nameless took upon Akivili's trailblazing legacy. When the Stellaron began to spread, the Star Rail also fell victim under its influence to the point where the train could barely function at all. As a result, the Nameless faction decided to abandon it after the rails have long been obstructed.

The Astral Express was later discovered by [[Himeko (honkai: star rail)|]] during her childhood, during which she became fascinated about the stories of the engine. She would repair the train years later to begin her journey across the universe.

In-game, it serves as the location for challenging content as well as the warp (gacha) feature.

title: heiter
body:
Heiter was the alcohol-loving priest of the Hero Party, which consisted of [[himmel (sousou no frieren)|Hero Himmel]], [[Frieren|Mage Frieren]], and [[eisen (sousou no frieren)|Warrior Eisen]]. Heiter is known as a drunkard, which is why Frieren calls him a "Corrupt Priest".

Many years later, he would adopt a [[aged down|young]] [[Fern (sousou no frieren)|]], who he would entrust to Frieren as an apprentice before he passed.

Heiter is a [[glasses|bespectacled]] Priest with short [[green hair]] that he keeps [[hair slicked back|slicked back]]. A few pieces of hair frame his face.

title: yuki_miku_(2022)
body:
"Grand Voyage ver"

The 2022 version of [[Yuki Miku]]. The theme of the design contest for this year was 海 (sea/ocean).

The winning entry was drawn by [[hamudetsu]] and features a naval captain [[sailor]] costume with a crab motif. She has [[heart-shaped pupils]] (or [[heart in eye]]) and wears a [[peaked cap]], red [[hair ribbon]] that resemble crab claws, and black [[fur-trimmed coat]] over a white [[double-breasted]] jacket over a [[red shirt]] with [[black necktie]]. She also wears black [[short shorts]] with red and white [[striped thighhighs]].

Her fan nicknames include Kani-chan (Crab-chan), Senchou-chan (Captain-chan), or Kani senchou-chan.

Her theme song is [[Kimiiro Marine Snow_(vocaloid)|]] by Carlos Hakamada.

title: yuki_miku_(2023)
body:
The 2023 version of [[Yuki Miku]]. The theme of the design contest for this year was 空模様 (weather/condition of the sky) showing the imagery of Hokkaido winter.

The winning entry was drawn by [[isakysaku]] and features a daybreak motif with a pastel palette. The main visual was illustrated by [[ancotaku]].

Her [[light blue hair]] ends with a [[pink hair|pink]] [[gradient hair|gradient]]. She wears a [[bonnet]] with a pink [[bowtie]]. Her [[twintails]] are adorned with [[sun_hair_ornament|sun]] and [[crescent_hair_ornament|crescent moon]] hair ornaments. She carries a giant [[paintbrush]] which she uses to paint the sky of the new day.

She is given the fan nickname 冬麗ちゃん (Fuyu Urara-chan) in Japanese, meaning "clear/beautiful winter". Her English fan nickname is "Serenity":[https://twitter.com/isaky_tm/status/1565583293935980544].

Her theme song is [[SnowMix_(vocaloid)|]] by Marasy, with PV illustrated by [[Omutatsu]].

title: columbo
body:
[b]Columbo[/b] is an American crime drama starring Peter Falk as [[lieutenant columbo|Lieutenant Columbo]], a homicide detective with the Los Angeles Police Department. The show originally aired from 1971 to 1978 and was later continue in a series of special episodes from 1989 to 2003.

Unlike most crime dramas where the hero finds clues and discovers the real culprit at the end of the episode, the culprit is seen in the beginning of the episode committing the crime and covering their tracks which Columbo later tries to figure out and prove how the culprit committed the crime.

title: masters_of_the_universe
body:
[i][b]Masters of the Universe[/b][/i] (commonly abbreviated [i][b]MOTU[/b][/i] and sometimes referred to as [i][b]He-Man and the Masters of the Universe[/b][/i] or just [i][b]He-Man[/b][/i], after the lead hero) is a [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] American media franchise created by the "Mattel toy company":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mattel in the early 80s.

Although featuring a vast line-up of characters, the main premise revolves around the conflict between the heroic [[He-Man]] and the evil [[Skeletor]] on [[eternia_(planet)|planet Eternia]]. 

Since its initial launch, the franchise has spawned a variety of products, including six lines of [[action figure]]s, four animated television series, several comic series, and a live action feature film (The "Japanese title":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%83%9E%E3%82%B9%E3%82%BF%E3%83%BC%E3%82%BA/%E8%B6%85%E7%A9%BA%E3%81%AE%E8%A6%87%E8%80%85 is usually only used for the movie).

The first cartoon series was broadcasted from 1983 to 1985. It became extremely popular in several different countries. 

A second animated spin-off series called [[She-Ra Princess of Power|She-Ra: Princess of Power]] was released in 1985. It also became quite popular, but not as much as the first series. It was rebooted in 2018 as [[She-Ra and the Princesses of Power]].

Designer Roger Sweet claims to be the chief creator of He-Man and MOTU, although this is not officially acknowledged by Mattel and is disputed by some other contributors. The earliest storybooks and much of the original backstory were written by Donald F. Glut, while the final production sculpt of the very first 1982 He-Man [[action figure]] was done by Tony Guerrero.

title: madness_(band)
body:
[b]Madness[/b] are an [[united_kingdom|English]] ska and pop band from Camden Town, north [[London]], who formed in 1976. One of the most prominent bands of the late 1970s and early 1980s two-tone ska revival, they continue to perform with six of the seven members of their original line-up. Madness's most successful period was from 1980 to 1986, when the band's songs spent a total of 214 weeks on the UK Singles Chart.

Madness have had 16 singles reach the UK top ten, including "One Step Beyond", "Baggy Trousers" and "It Must Be Love", one UK number-one single "House of Fun" and two number ones in Ireland, "House of Fun" and "Wings of a Dove". 

"Our House" was their biggest US hit, reaching number 7 on the Billboard Hot 100. In 2000, the band received the Ivor Novello Award from the British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors for Outstanding Song Collection.

title: macross_2
body:
[b][i]The Super Dimension Fortress Macross II: Lovers Again[/i][/b] (超時空要塞マクロスII [i]Lovers Again[/i], "Chō Ji-kū Yō-sai Ma-ku-ro-su" II - Lovers Again?), also known as [b]Super Dimensional Fortress Macross II[/b] or simply [b][i]Macross II[/i][/b], is the first animated sequel to [[choujikuu_yousai_macross|The Super Dimension Fortress Macross]] to feature a new cast of characters. This [[japan]]ese [[mecha]] anime OVA was released in May 21, 1992.

This series was produced by Big West only and is notable because it's the only [[Macross]] production that was developed without Studio Nue's and [[Kawamori Shouji]]'s (the original series creator and mecha designer) involvement. 

[[Mikimoto Haruhiko]] designed the new characters while Okuda Atsushi, Akutsu Junichi, Fujita Kazumi and [[Oohata Kouichi]] designed the mecha.

The story takes place in the year 2092, eighty years after the events depicted in the anime film [i]The Super Dimension Fortress Macross: Do You Remember Love?[/i]

Originally promoted as a canon sequel to the [[Macross: Do You Remember Love?]] theatrical movie, Macross II has since been relegated by Studio Nue as taking place in an alternate continuity and is no longer considered part of the original series canon. However, many books, toys, [[video game]]s and other officially sponsored products related to the series are still being produced.

title: order_of_the_red_banner
body:
A [[Soviet]] military decoration for heroism in combat, awarded from 1924-1991. Originally the highest honor in the Soviet armed forces, until surpassed by the [[Order of Lenin]] in 1930; however, the latter was not strictly reserved for military heroism. 

It consists of a white enamel badge with a golden [[hammer and sickle]], a red star, [[gold trim]] of wheat, and crossed items including a red flag with the motto "Workers of the World, unite" etched on it.

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_Red_Banner]

title: order_of_the_patriotic_war
body:
A [[Soviet]] military decoration that was awarded to armed regulars, security, and partisans during [[World War II]] (also known as the Great Patriotic War, hence the order's name). 

It consists of a gold/silver rayed five-pointed star alongside a red five-pointed star, crossed with a saber and a Mosin-Nagant, and a central disc with the [[hammer and sickle]] inside. Certain portrayals (such as [[Pamiat Merkuria (retrofit) (azur lane)|]]) may replace the communist symbol for another to be acceptable to certain audiences, and/or may omit the crossed weapons. 

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_Patriotic_War]

title: cumulonimbus_cloud
body:
A dense, towering vertical [[cloud]].

Well-developed cumulonimbus clouds are characterized by a flat, anvil-like top (anvil dome), caused by wind shear or inversion near the boundary between the troposphere and the stratosphere.  These clouds are capable of producing lightning and other dangerous severe weather, such as tornadoes and hailstones.

h4. Types

* Cumulonimbus calvus: Latin for "bald", features a puffy top
* Cumulonimbus capillatus: Latin for "long hair", features ice crystal clouds that streak out at its top edge giving it a fibrous appearance
* Cumulonimbus capillatus incus: Also known as an "anvil cloud" (incus being Latin for anvil), features a flat, anvil-top shape

h4. Examples

* !post #2666937
* !post #3326870
* !post #4594627

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Cumulonimbus cloud":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulonimbus_cloud

title: sett
body:
A sett, usually the plural setts and in some places called a Belgian block, is a broadly rectangular quarried stone used originally for paving roads, today a decorative stone [[pavement|paving]] used in landscape architecture. Often incorrectly called "[[cobblestone]]". A sett is distinct from a cobblestone by being quarried or shaped to a regular form, whereas a cobblestone is generally naturally occurring.

title: london_calling
body:
[i]London Calling[/i] is a rock music album made by the English band [b][[The Clash]][/b] in 1979. The iconic "album cover":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:TheClashLondonCallingalbumcover.jpg] shows Paul Simonon violently smashing his bass against the floor. The remnants of the broken bass are on display in the "Museum of London":[https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/museum-london/whats-on/exhibitions/clash-simonon-bass-guitar-display] ("archived":[https://web.archive.org/web/20240106203300/https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/museum-london/whats-on/exhibitions/clash-simonon-bass-guitar-display]).

title: druze_star
body:
A [b]multicoloured [[pentagram]][/b] that symbolize the [b]five colours[/b] ("Five Limits" خمس حدود khams ḥudūd) of [b]Druze[/b] esoteric ethnoreligious group, despite the faith avoids iconography. The usage is as popular as the five-coloured flag with horizontal stripes. 

Each of the colors representing the five limits pertains to a metaphysical power called ḥadd, literally "a limit", as in the distinctions that separate humans from animals, or the powers that make humans the animalistic body. Each ḥadd is color-coded in the following manner:
* [b]Green[/b] for ʻAql "the Universal Mind/Intelligence/Nous",
* [b]Red[/b] for Nafs "the Universal Soul/Anima mundi",
* [b]Yellow[/b] for Kalima "the Word/Logos",
* [b]Blue[/b] for Sābiq (السابق) "the anterior/potentiality/cause/precedent", the first intellect.
* [b]White[/b] for al-llahiq (اللاحق) "the posterior/future/effect/Immanence".

The five-pointed star embodies the golden ratio, phi, as a symbol of temperance and a life of moderation. 
This looks similar with the Imperial Chinese "Beiyang Army":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beiyang_Army] symbol, but one side is [b]green[/b] instead of black.

* !asset #20083696

h4. External links
* [[tag group:symbols|list of symbols]]
* "symbols.com":[https://www.symbols.com/symbol/druze-star]
* Wikipedia article: "Druze":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Druze#Religious_symbol]

title: anson_(azur_lane)
body:
[i][[Azur Lane]][/i]'s planned personification of the battleship HMS [i]Anson[/i] (79).

Notably, she has a drastically different design compared to her sister ships, particularly being more [[loli|petite]] in size, and wearing a [[school swimsuit]]. This design was cancelled due to a backlash from playerbase, as the design was deemed "unfit" for her actual classification, with some believing that the design was originally intended to be used on a submarine shipgirl. Her place in the [i]From Zero to Hero[/i] event on March 28, 2024 was taken up by [[Friedrich Carl (Azur Lane)|]] as a solution while Anson is being redesigned. 

* !post #7365603: [[Anson (azur lane)|Default]]

body:
[[vajra_(granblue_fantasy)|Vajra]] in her swimsuit.

body:

title: long_sword
body:
A longsword is a type of European sword characterized as having a cruciform hilt with a grip for two-handed use.

A western-style/European sword used with two hands, typically from stomach height to armpit height. Any sword about as tall or taller than the wielder is a [[greatsword]]. Any shorter sword of the same style that can reasonably be held with only one hand is an arming [[sword]].

body:
[b]Omicient Reader's Viewpoint[/b] (전지적 독자 시점) is a apocalyptic fantasy fiction webnovel, written by a Korean author duo writing under the pen name Sing Shong. It was originally written in Korean, and has been translated to English by Webnovel translators RainbowTurtle and A Passing Wanderer.

The series recently released a manhwa/webtoon produced by Redice Studio and published by Naver Webtoon.

title: priapus
body:
Doujinshi artist [[itto_(mentaiko)]]'s [[bara]] [[doujinshi]] manga inspired by the Priapus mythos in 2011. 


Summary: 
[quote] Zeus is sick of all the hate, envy, and violence that humans cause on Earth. So he gives Priapus the important task of making all human males homosexual, in order to destroy any means of humans to leave behind children. Priapus descends to earth, meeting his first target, Ousuke Sakura. Part 2: Priapus continues the mission that Zeus sent him on. This time Priapus ends up in rural Japan and meets his next target, Honda, a police officer.[/quote]

It got so popular it even has gotten its own official English release.
From "Amazon":[https://www.amazon.com/Priapus-by-Mentaiko-1-Apr-2015-Paperback/dp/B011T72V4U] :
[quote] You can't imagine Japan's manga scene without Mentaiko Itto's amusing gay mangas anymore. Bruno Gm nder now publishes his works for the first time in English, introducing him to a broader audience. [/quote]

title: kagurabachi
body:
Weekly Shonen Jump manga series created by [[Hokazono Takeru]] in 2023, following the story of [[Rokuhira Chihiro]].


Prior to its debut, its first chapter was leaked a week ahead of time. In response to several elements in the chapter itself, as well as the overarching discourse at the time over WSJ's line-up, the manga received an abnormal amount of attention on the online West, ironically labeling it the magazine's new torchbearer in a meme campaign comparable to that of [[Morbius (film)|]], which then promptly led many to label it an 'industry plant'. Typical references to the meme include [[kagurabachi pose (meme)|edits and redraws]] of the "key art":[/posts/6707029] released with the manga's debut "announcement":[https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2294136/full/]. The aftermath of the meme would see appreciation for the manga go from the ironic to the sincere, due to its genuine quality.

title: i've_never_seen_a_guy_recreate_this_successfully_tbh_(meme)
body:
A meme  focusing on characters, often men, trying on and being unable to wear [[undersized clothes|undersized]] [[open pants|pants]] because of the size of their [[ass]] and [[bulge]]. The meme  sprung out from a Tweet by Vessyteena captioned "I've never seen a guy recreate this successfully tbh":[/media_assets/8329126] with a cropped version of [[suko mugi]]'s [i][[Hypnosis Mic]][/i] comic (post #6149751) , which depicts [[Busujima Rio Mason]] doing the same in a fitting room.

The tweet picked up steam within the fandom and the BL and [[bara]] communities, with imitators dropping the fitting room context and sometimes adding [[motion lines]] like  in the original comic. Variations of the meme will often have the characters be drawn as [[topless male|topless]], unlike the original which kept Busujima fully clothed.

h4. Examples
* !post #6149751: Origin
* !post #6153730
* !post #6190550

h4. External Links 
* "The Original Tweet":https://twitter.com/Vessyteena/status/1635675730129588229

title: rinne_sharingan
body:
The Rinne Sharingan (literally meaning: Saṃsāra Copy Wheel Eye) is a dōjutsu kekkei mōra and the predecessor to the [[Rinnegan]] and [[Sharingan]] (and by extension their in-between stage, the [[Mangekyou Sharingan]]).

It is characterised by red sclerae and irides, with a [[ringed_eyes|ripple pattern]] spreading over the [[eyeball]] and nine [[tomoe (symbol)|]]. In its sole known user, it acts as a [[third eye]].

Note that [[uchiha sasuke|Sasuke]]’s variant of the Rinnegan is often tagged using this tag, even though that’s technically incorrect.

h4. Examples
* !post #7412733: [[Uchiha Sasuke|Sasuke]]'s [[Rinnegan]]

h5. Known users

* [[Ootsutsuki Kaguya]]

h4.See also

* [[Tag Group:Eyes Tags]]

title: chisel
body:
A chisel is a wedged hand tool with a characteristically shaped cutting edge on the end of its blade, for carving or cutting a hard material (e.g. wood, stone, or metal). The tool can be used by hand, struck with a mallet, or applied with mechanical power.
 
The handle and blade of some types of chisel are made of metal or wood with a sharp edge in it.
